Authentication and Authorization in Jenkins are two separate concepts:

Authentication: Verifies who the user is (username/password, LDAP, Active Directory, GitHub OAuth, SAML, etc.).
Authorization: Determines what the authenticated user is allowed to do (admin, developer, read-only, etc.).



Authentication: 

Manage Jenkins
    ↓
Security
    ↓
Users (Create User)


Authorization:

Manage Jenkins
↓
Security -> Matrix-based security(At Job Level applies to all jobs same authorization) -> Click on Add Users (Give permission to user like Build Job, View Job, Configure Job)


To implement Specify User needs to access only specific jobs (Role-based strategy)

Manage Jenkins
→ Security -> Role-Based Strategy -> save

Manage Jenkins → Manage and Assign Roles → Manage Roles

Under Job Roles, create a role such as:
    Role Name	Pattern
    Build-App1	^App1$

The pattern uses a regular expression:

^App1$ → matches only the job named App1
^Dev-.* → matches all jobs starting with Dev-
.* → matches every job



Matrix-based Security (configured under Manage Jenkins → Security) applies globally. The permissions you assign there apply to all jobs in Jenkins.

For example:

User	Overall Read	Job Read	Job Build	Result
saivarma	✅	✅	✅	Can build every job
tester	    ✅	✅	❌	Can view every job but cannot build any

There is no way to restrict access to only specific jobs using the global Matrix-based Security alone.




Jenkins Roles
├── Global (Jenkins itself)
├── Items (Jobs, Pipelines, Folders)
└── Agents (Build Nodes)
